{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Core Challenge: 3D Is Underspecified by Text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A text prompt like \"a ceramic owl figurine\" describes how an object looks from any viewpoint simultaneously — yet 2D training data only ever shows individual views. Text-to-3D models must generate a complete 3D representation that is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "multi-view consistent"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": every 2D render of the 3D output, from any camera angle, must look photorealistic and match the prompt. This is fundamentally harder than image generation because the output must encode geometry (shape) and appearance (texture) jointly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Two paradigms have emerged: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "score distillation sampling (SDS)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", which uses a 2D diffusion model as a loss function to optimise a 3D representation from scratch, and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "feed-forward generation"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", which trains a model to output a 3D structure directly in a single forward pass."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Text-to-3D paradigms: SDS/DreamFusion optimisation loop (left) vs feed-forward generation with Shap-E (right), plus model comparison table"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Paradigm 1: Score Distillation Sampling (DreamFusion)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "DreamFusion (Poole et al., 2022) introduced SDS — the insight that a pre-trained 2D diffusion model can act as a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "differentiable loss function"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for optimising a 3D representation. The algorithm:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Initialise a NeRF (neural radiance field) with random weights."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Sample a random camera pose and render a 2D image from the NeRF."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Add random noise at timestep t to the rendered image, producing a noisy image xₜ."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Run the frozen 2D diffusion model: predict the noise ε_φ(xₜ; c, t) conditioned on the text embedding c."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "The SDS gradient is the difference between the predicted noise and the actual added noise, scaled by the diffusion model's score. This gradient flows back through the renderer into the NeRF weights."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Repeat for ~10 000 steps. The NeRF learns to produce renderings that the diffusion model scores as high-probability under the text condition."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The SDS gradient is:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\nabla_\\theta \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{SDS}} = \\mathbb{E}_{t,\\epsilon}\\!\\left[w(t)\\,\\bigl(\\hat{\\epsilon}_\\phi(\\mathbf{x}_t; \\mathbf{c}, t) - \\epsilon\\bigr)\\,\\frac{\\partial \\mathbf{x}}{\\partial \\theta}\\right]"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "where "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "w(t)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is a time-dependent weighting, "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "x"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the rendered image, and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "θ"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " are the NeRF parameters. The term "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "∂x/∂θ"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the gradient of the renderer — available because NeRF rendering is differentiable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "SDS Limitation: The Saturation and Blurriness Problem"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "SDS outputs are notorious for being "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "over-saturated and blurry"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " — a phenomenon called the \"Janus problem\" (objects grow multiple fronts). The gradient variance is high because every step uses a different noise level, and the diffusion model's score function averages over many plausible outputs. Variational Score Distillation (VSD, used in ProlificDreamer) fixes this by replacing the single-sample SDS gradient with a proper variational distribution, producing significantly sharper results at the cost of more computation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Paradigm 2: Feed-Forward 3D Generation (Shap-E)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OpenAI's Shap-E (Jun et al., 2023) trains a diffusion model directly "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "over the parameter space of implicit 3D functions"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Given a 3D object dataset, Shap-E first trains an encoder that maps each 3D object into a compact latent vector representing the weights of an implicit neural field (NeRF or textured mesh). A diffusion model then learns to generate these latent vectors from text or image conditioning."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "At inference, a single forward pass through the diffusion model produces a latent that decodes into a complete NeRF. The NeRF can then be converted to a mesh via marching cubes. This approach is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "100–1000× faster than SDS"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " but requires large amounts of paired (3D object, text caption) training data, which limits diversity."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Shap-E: Text-to-3D in Practice"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install shap-e\nimport torch\nfrom shap_e.diffusion.sample import sample_latents\nfrom shap_e.diffusion.gaussian_diffusion import diffusion_from_config\nfrom shap_e.models.download import load_model, load_config\nfrom shap_e.util.notebooks import decode_latent_mesh\nimport trimesh\n\ndevice = torch.device(\"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\")\n\n# Load the text-to-3D model and the latent diffusion model\nxm     = load_model(\"transmitter\", device=device)\nmodel  = load_model(\"text300M\", device=device)   # text-conditioned\ndiffusion = diffusion_from_config(load_config(\"diffusion\"))\n\nbatch_size = 1\nguidance_scale = 15.0\nprompt = \"a ceramic owl figurine, studio lighting, detailed feathers\"\n\nlatents = sample_latents(\n    batch_size=batch_size,\n    model=model,\n    diffusion=diffusion,\n    guidance_scale=guidance_scale,\n    model_kwargs=dict(texts=[prompt] * batch_size),\n    progress=True,\n    clip_denoised=True,\n    use_fp16=True,\n    use_karras=True,\n    karras_steps=64,\n    sigma_min=1e-3,\n    sigma_max=160,\n    s_churn=0,\n)\n\n# Decode the latent into a textured mesh\nfor i, latent in enumerate(latents):\n    t = decode_latent_mesh(xm, latent).tri_mesh()\n    mesh = trimesh.Trimesh(\n        vertices=t.verts,\n        faces=t.faces,\n        vertex_colors=t.vertex_channels,\n    )\n    mesh.export(f\"owl_{i}.obj\")\n    print(f\"Saved owl_{i}.obj ({len(mesh.vertices)} vertices, {len(mesh.faces)} faces)\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Shap-E: Image-to-3D"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Shap-E also supports conditioning on an input image, which significantly improves 3D fidelity because the image provides explicit appearance information:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from shap_e.models.download import load_model, load_config\nfrom shap_e.diffusion.sample import sample_latents\nfrom shap_e.diffusion.gaussian_diffusion import diffusion_from_config\nfrom shap_e.util.image_util import load_image\nfrom shap_e.util.notebooks import decode_latent_mesh\nimport torch, trimesh\n\ndevice = torch.device(\"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\")\n\n# Image-conditioned model\nxm       = load_model(\"transmitter\", device=device)\nmodel    = load_model(\"image300M\", device=device)   # image-conditioned\ndiffusion = diffusion_from_config(load_config(\"diffusion\"))\n\n# Load a reference image (RGBA PNG, ~256x256 recommended)\nimage = load_image(\"reference_object.png\")\n\nlatents = sample_latents(\n    batch_size=1,\n    model=model,\n    diffusion=diffusion,\n    guidance_scale=3.0,      # lower scale works better for image conditioning\n    model_kwargs=dict(images=[image]),\n    progress=True,\n    clip_denoised=True,\n    use_fp16=True,\n    use_karras=True,\n    karras_steps=64,\n    sigma_min=1e-3,\n    sigma_max=160,\n    s_churn=0,\n)\n\nt = decode_latent_mesh(xm, latents[0]).tri_mesh()\ntrimesh.Trimesh(t.verts, t.faces, vertex_colors=t.vertex_channels).export(\"from_image.glb\")\nprint(\"Saved from_image.glb\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Point-E: Point Clouds as an Intermediate Step"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OpenAI's Point-E (Nichol et al., 2022) is a faster but lower-quality predecessor to Shap-E. It generates a 3D "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "point cloud"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (a set of coloured 3D points) from a text or image prompt and then optionally fits a mesh to it. The two-stage pipeline — first generate a coarse point cloud in ~1 minute, then refine — makes it practical for quick iteration:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install point-e\nimport torch\nfrom tqdm.auto import tqdm\nfrom PIL import Image\nfrom point_e.diffusion.configs import DIFFUSION_CONFIGS, diffusion_from_config\nfrom point_e.diffusion.sampler import PointCloudSampler\nfrom point_e.models.download import load_checkpoint\nfrom point_e.models.configs import MODEL_CONFIGS, model_from_config\nfrom point_e.util.plotting import plot_point_cloud\n\ndevice = torch.device(\"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\")\nprint(\"Loading models...\")\n\n# Stage 1: generate a low-resolution point cloud from text (1024 pts)\nbase_name = \"base40M-textvec\"\nbase_model = model_from_config(MODEL_CONFIGS[base_name], device)\nbase_model.load_state_dict(load_checkpoint(base_name, device))\nbase_diffusion = diffusion_from_config(DIFFUSION_CONFIGS[base_name])\n\n# Stage 2: upsample to 4096 points\nupsample_name = \"upsample\"\nupsampler_model = model_from_config(MODEL_CONFIGS[upsample_name], device)\nupsampler_model.load_state_dict(load_checkpoint(upsample_name, device))\nupsample_diffusion = diffusion_from_config(DIFFUSION_CONFIGS[upsample_name])\n\nsampler = PointCloudSampler(\n    device=device,\n    models=[base_model, upsampler_model],\n    diffusions=[base_diffusion, upsample_diffusion],\n    num_points=[1024, 4096 - 1024],\n    aux_channels=[\"R\", \"G\", \"B\"],\n    guidance_scale=[3.0, 0.0],\n)\n\nprompt = \"a detailed antique clock with roman numerals\"\nsamples = None\nfor x in tqdm(sampler.sample_batch_progressive(\n    batch_size=1,\n    model_kwargs=dict(texts=[prompt]),\n)):\n    samples = x\n\npc = sampler.output_to_point_clouds(samples)[0]\nfig = plot_point_cloud(pc, grid_size=3, fixed_bounds=((-0.75, -0.75, -0.75), (0.75, 0.75, 0.75)))\nfig.savefig(\"point_cloud_preview.png\", dpi=120)\nprint(f\"Point cloud: {pc.coords.shape[0]} points\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Zero123++: Multi-View Diffusion for High-Fidelity Reconstruction"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A newer and more powerful approach is to first synthesise multiple views of the 3D object from a single input image, then reconstruct the 3D mesh from those views. Zero123++ (Shi et al., 2023) fine-tunes Stable Diffusion to generate 6 novel views of an object given one reference image and the target camera angles. A separate multi-view reconstruction network (e.g. InstantMesh or One-2-3-45) then turns those 6 views into a watertight mesh."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This pipeline achieves the best quality among open-source methods because it separates appearance synthesis (what the 2D diffusion model is good at) from geometric reconstruction (what the multi-view stereo solver is good at):"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Zero123++ generates 6 views in a 3×2 grid from one input image\n# pip install diffusers transformers accelerate pillow\nimport torch\nfrom diffusers import DiffusionPipeline, EulerAncestralDiscreteScheduler\nfrom PIL import Image\nimport numpy as np\n\npipe = DiffusionPipeline.from_pretrained(\n    \"sudo-ai/zero123plus-v1.2\",\n    custom_pipeline=\"sudo-ai/zero123plus-pipeline\",\n    torch_dtype=torch.float16,\n)\npipe.scheduler = EulerAncestralDiscreteScheduler.from_config(\n    pipe.scheduler.config,\n    timestep_spacing=\"trailing\",\n)\npipe.to(\"cuda\")\n\n# Input: a single image of the object (use rembg to remove background first)\ncond_image = Image.open(\"object_nobg.png\").convert(\"RGBA\")\n\n# Output: a 3x2 grid of 6 novel views at fixed azimuth offsets\nresult = pipe(\n    cond_image,\n    num_inference_steps=36,\n    generator=torch.manual_seed(42),\n).images[0]                              # single PIL image: 960x640 (6 × 320x320)\n\n# Split the grid into individual views\ndef split_grid(img, rows=3, cols=2):\n    w, h = img.size\n    tw, th = w // cols, h // rows\n    views = []\n    for r in range(rows):\n        for c in range(cols):\n            box = (c * tw, r * th, (c + 1) * tw, (r + 1) * th)\n            views.append(img.crop(box))\n    return views\n\nviews = split_grid(result)\nfor i, view in enumerate(views):\n    view.save(f\"view_{i:02d}.png\")\nprint(f\"Generated {len(views)} novel views\")\n\n# Next step: feed these 6 views into a reconstruction network\n# (e.g. One-2-3-45, InstantMesh) to obtain a watertight mesh"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Exporting and Working with Generated 3D Meshes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "All methods ultimately produce a mesh. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "trimesh"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " library is the standard tool for loading, inspecting, cleaning, and exporting 3D meshes in Python:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install trimesh[easy]\nimport trimesh\nimport numpy as np\n\n# Load a mesh produced by any text-to-3D model\nmesh = trimesh.load(\"owl.obj\")\nprint(f\"Vertices: {len(mesh.vertices)}\")\nprint(f\"Faces:    {len(mesh.faces)}\")\nprint(f\"Watertight: {mesh.is_watertight}\")\nprint(f\"Bounding box: {mesh.bounds}\")\n\n# Centre and normalise to unit sphere (common pre-processing)\nmesh.vertices -= mesh.center_mass\nscale = np.linalg.norm(mesh.vertices, axis=1).max()\nmesh.vertices /= scale\n\n# Smooth and simplify\nmesh = trimesh.smoothing.filter_laplacian(mesh, lamb=0.5, iterations=3)\nmesh = mesh.simplify_quadratic_decimation(target_count=5000)  # reduce face count\n\n# Export to multiple formats\nmesh.export(\"owl_clean.obj\")    # Wavefront OBJ\nmesh.export(\"owl_clean.glb\")    # Binary glTF — best for web/AR\nmesh.export(\"owl_clean.stl\")    # for 3D printing\n\n# Render 8 turntable views for visual inspection\nscene  = trimesh.Scene(mesh)\nangles = np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, 8, endpoint=False)\nfor i, angle in enumerate(angles):\n    scene.set_camera(angles=[0, angle, 0])\n    png_bytes = scene.save_image(resolution=(256, 256))\n    with open(f\"view_{i}.png\", \"wb\") as f:\n        f.write(png_bytes)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
